{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8a25c56d-0edf-4143-b784-4311082bc55a","content":"Based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI (no repo-specific docs found here):\n\n**1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — Yes, this is still valid in .NET MAUI on .NET 10, but make sure you're using the **MAUI namespace**, not the old Xamarin.Forms one:\n\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n```\n\nThen `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` on your `ContentPage` will add padding to keep content out of the notch/Dynamic Island area.\n\n**2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on a Grid** — This is **not a valid property** on `Grid` or `VisualElement` in .NET MAUI. That sounds like outdated or incorrect tutorial guidance.\n\nFor a background image that extends edge-to-edge (behind the notch), use one of these approaches instead:\n\n- **Page-level background:**\n  ```xml\n  <ContentPage.Background>\n      <ImageBrush ImageSource=\"background.png\" />\n  </ContentPage.Background>\n  ```\n\n- **Or** place an `Image` with `Aspect=\"AspectFill\"` in the same Grid row/column as your content but *without* `UseSafeArea` on the page, and manually apply safe-area padding to the content overlay.\n\nThe first approach (ImageBrush) is simplest for a full-bleed background while still using `UseSafeArea` for your foreground content.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"79e4c4ca-94ac-45ac-8916-1c0c3047d70b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository doesn't have relevant content about MAUI safe areas. Let me answer based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI APIs.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the safe area handling has evolved:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - This is a **Xamarin.Forms** API (using the `ios` platform-specific namespace). In .NET MAUI, the approach changed. The equivalent in .NET MAUI is handled differently.\n\n2. In .NET MAUI, safe area insets are handled through padding automatically, or you can use the `Page.IgnoreSafeArea` property or set padding manually.\n\n\n3. Actually, let me clarify: in Xamarin.Forms you had platform-specific safe area handling, but .NET MAUI respects safe areas by default on iOS pages. If you need content to extend into the safe area (like background images), you'd use `IgnoreSafeArea` on specific layouts or views rather than at the page level. individual views, you can set them to ignore safe area\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully:\n\nIn .NET MAUI (.NET 6+):\n- Pages automatically respect safe areas on iOS - there's no need for `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` because that's the Xamarin.Forms platform-specific API\n- The MAUI equivalent behavior is built-in by default\n- For views that should extend into unsafe areas (like background images), you can use padding manipulation or specific layout techniques\n\nWait, I need to be more careful here. Let me think about what's actually in .NET MAUI:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the safe area handling works by default on iOS, and I can use the `IgnoreSafeArea` property on individual views to extend them edge-to-edge. The platform-specific namespace changed from Xamarin.Forms to use `Microsoft.Maui.Controls.P` in MAUI, and while `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` still exists as a platform-specific API, the safe area behavior is now handled automatically by default.\n\nSo to clarify: `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` is valid in .NET MAUI with the updated namespace, but it's not necessary since safe areas are respected by default. The `IgnoreSafeArea` property on Grid isn't a standard MAUI API - that's not how you extend layouts into unsafe areas in MAUI. So the iOS-specific approach with `UseSafeArea` is definitely the right way to go in MAUI, but I'm less certain about whether `IgnoreSafeArea` exists as a direct property on Grid—for edge-to-edge backgrounds, I'd need to rely on alternative techniques like negative margins or background positioning instead.","outputTokens":1592,"requestId":"500C:802C:1A997F